,"1335":"1335","after 22 March 1279":"after 22 March 1279","1279":"1279","1256":"1256","1355":"1355","1254":"1254","about 11 November 1292":"about 11 November 1292","about 1279":"about 1279","about 1302":"about 1302","Wiston, Sussex, England":"Wiston, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Upton Scudamore, Wiltshire, England":"Upton Scudamore, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","of Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bavant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Shrikant, Narayan, Paras, Rakesh, Sapna, Smita.","French and Italian (Piedmont): probably a variant of   Salvant  .","Indian (Maharashtra): from Sanskrit title <i>sāmanta</i> ‘feudatory prince’, a variant of <i>sawant</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Salvant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Cyrille, Lucien, Michel.","French: variant of <b>Sauvant</b>, from an old vernacular form of the personal name   Sylvain  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Bavant I was born on 22 March 1279, in Wiston, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam de Bavant II, was 26 and his mother, Alice de Scudamore, was 24. He married Joan of England about 1302, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 15 July 1335."},"et":{"22 March 1279–after 15 July 1335":"22. märts 1279–pärast 15. juulit 1335","1279–1335":"1279–1335","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1313–1355":"1313–1355","1254–1292":"1254–1292","1256–1293":"1256–1293","22 March 1279":"22. märts 1279","after 15 July 1335":"pärast 15. juulit 1335","1293":"1293","1282":"1282","1292":"1292","1313":"1313","1335":"1335","after 22 March 1279":"pärast 22. märtsi 1279","1279":"1279","1256":"1256","1355":"1355","1254":"1254","about 11 November 1292":"umbes 11. november 1292","about 1279":"umbes 1279","about 1302":"umbes 1302","Wiston, Sussex, England":"Wiston, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Upton Scudamore, Wiltshire, England":"Upton Scudamore, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","of Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"22 March 1279–after 15 July 1335":"22. maaliskuuta 1279–15. heinäkuuta 1335 jälkeen","1279–1335":"1279–1335","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","13